      modelAnswer: 'Radioactive isotopes are widely used in medicine. Diagnostic tracers, such as technetium-99m with its 6-hour half-life, are introduced into the body and tracked using gamma cameras to image organ function or detect blockages. Radiotherapy uses gamma sources, proton beams or beta-emitting implants to kill cancer cells; multiple beams are crossed at the tumour to deliver a high dose while sparing surrounding healthy tissue. Gamma irradiation is also used to sterilise medical equipment by killing bacteria. Benefits include non-invasive diagnosis, effective treatment of otherwise inoperable cancers and reliable sterilisation. However, ionising radiation can damage healthy DNA, increasing the long-term risk of cancer for patients and staff. Risks are managed by using the lowest effective dose, choosing isotopes with short half-lives, shielding staff with lead, restricting exposure time, training operators and continually monitoring doses. International standards govern source supply and disposal. On balance, the medical benefits typically outweigh the risks when proper procedures are followed.'
