      q: 'Describe the principles of magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and assess its advantages and limitations as a medical imaging technique.',
      marks: 12, command: 'Describe',
      modelAnswer: 'In MRI, the patient is placed in a strong, uniform magnetic field; the magnetic moments of hydrogen nuclei (mostly in body water and fat) align partly with the field. Pulses of radio-frequency electromagnetic radiation, tuned to the Larmor frequency, flip the alignment of the nuclei. After each pulse, the nuclei relax back to alignment with the static field, emitting their own radio signal whose strength and decay time depend on the local tissue. Gradient coils superimpose smaller, position-dependent fields so different parts of the body resonate at slightly different frequencies, allowing the signals to be spatially mapped and reconstructed by a computer into 3D images. Advantages: MRI uses non-ionising radiation, so it carries no cancer risk; it gives excellent soft-tissue contrast, especially of the brain, ligaments, organs and tumours, where X-ray CT shows little detail; and it provides 3D, cross-sectional images. Limitations: scanners are very expensive to buy and maintain; the strong magnetic field excludes patients with ferromagnetic implants or pacemakers; scans are slow and the patient must remain still in a confined space, which can cause anxiety. Despite these limitations, MRI is one of the most powerful diagnostic tools in modern medicine.'
