      modelAnswer: 'X-ray imaging uses high-frequency electromagnetic radiation produced by accelerating electrons into a metal target. X-rays pass through the body and are absorbed by dense tissues such as bones more strongly than by soft tissues, producing shadow images on a detector. They show bone fractures and high-density features clearly but distinguish soft tissues poorly. X-rays are ionising and can damage DNA, so doses are kept as low as possible and pregnant women are usually not scanned. Ultrasound uses pulses of high-frequency sound (above 20 kHz) emitted by a transducer; reflections from tissue boundaries are timed and used to construct images. It distinguishes soft tissues well and can image moving structures such as the heart in real time, and the developing foetus during pregnancy. Ultrasound is non-ionising and is considered safe for repeated use, even during pregnancy. Limitations of ultrasound include difficulty imaging through bone or air pockets, and lower resolution than X-rays for hard tissues. The two techniques are therefore complementary, with the choice depending on the clinical question and patient considerations.'
