      modelAnswer: 'A Geiger–Müller (GM) tube uses a low-pressure gas with a high-voltage anode wire; ionising radiation entering through a thin window ionises gas atoms, causing an avalanche that produces a large pulse counted by external electronics. GM tubes are simple, robust and cheap, and respond to alpha (with a thin window), beta and gamma. Limitations include a dead time of ~100 μs that underestimates count rates, no information about particle type or energy, and limited gamma efficiency. A scintillation counter uses a phosphor that emits a flash of light when struck by radiation; the flash is detected by a photomultiplier tube and the pulse height is proportional to the radiation\'s energy. Scintillators have shorter dead time, better gamma efficiency, and energy resolution that allows different radiation types to be distinguished. Drawbacks include higher cost, complexity, and sensitivity to temperature and magnetic fields. The GM tube is well suited to simple counting applications such as portable contamination monitors; scintillation counters are preferred for spectroscopy, medical imaging (e.g. gamma cameras and PET) and high-rate experiments where detail matters.'
